{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/acute-childhood-limp/background-information/definition/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"3d33154e-2fa7-524d-8ee5-88a6b5de9cae","slug":"definition","fullItemName":"Definition","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 2e128c6c-792d-4116-a0c1-5e00d7203e2e --><h2>What is it?</h2><!-- end field 2e128c6c-792d-4116-a0c1-5e00d7203e2e -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item 479e598c-957a-4885-a1ff-a183e8a96e4e --><!-- begin field 2fa560c7-78dd-4610-ad88-4e134f68dacb --><ul><li><strong>A limp is defined as an asymmetric gait, and is a deviation from <strong><span class=\"NormalTextRun  BCX0 SCXW179920610\">a normal age-appropriate gait pattern [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/acute-childhood-limp/references/\">Naranje, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/acute-childhood-limp/references/\">BMJ, 2018a</a>].</span></strong></strong><ul><li>A child develops a mature gait pattern at age 3 years, and it consists of a stance phase, during which the foot is in contact with the ground, and a swing phase, during which the foot is in the air [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/acute-childhood-limp/references/\">Naranje, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/acute-childhood-limp/references/\">Shah, 2015</a>]. </li><li>A limp is a clinical presentation and not a diagnosis, and is secondary to pain, weakness, or deformity as a result of a variety of <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/acute-childhood-limp/diagnosis/differential-diagnosis/\">conditions</a> [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/acute-childhood-limp/references/\">Davis, 2017</a>].</li></ul></li><li><strong>Antalgic gait is the most common type of limp encountered in children.</strong><ul><li>There is a shortening of the stance phase and an increase of the swing phase, with the child 'hurrying' off one leg to offload a source of pain [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/acute-childhood-limp/references/\">Perry, 2010</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/acute-childhood-limp/references/\">Herman, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/acute-childhood-limp/references/\">Adamson, 2020</a>].</li><li>This type of gait results typically from trauma or an infection [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/acute-childhood-limp/references/\">Shah, 2015</a>].</li></ul></li><li><strong>Nonantalgic gaits are less common and include <strong>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/acute-childhood-limp/references/\">Shah, 2015</a>]</strong></strong><strong>:</strong><ul><li>A Trendelenburg gait — where the pelvis exhibits a downward tilt towards the unaffected side during the swing phase because of weakness in the contralateral gluteus medius muscle. This type of gait is usually seen in disorders of the hip, such as <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/acute-childhood-limp/diagnosis/differential-diagnosis/\">developmental dysplasia of the hip</a>, <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/acute-childhood-limp/diagnosis/differential-diagnosis/\">Perthes' disease</a>, or <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/acute-childhood-limp/diagnosis/differential-diagnosis/\">slipped capital femoral epiphysis</a>.</li><li>A steppage gait — results from excessive flexion of the hip and knee joints during the swing phase due to an inability to dorsiflex the foot. This type of gait is seen in children with cerebral palsy and other neurologic disorders.</li><li>A vaulting or circumduction gait — results from hyperextension and locking of the knees at the end of the stance phase and the child must vault over the affected extremity. This type of gait is usually associated with a limb-length discrepancy or a mechanical disorder leading to abnormal knee mobility.</li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 2fa560c7-78dd-4610-ad88-4e134f68dacb --><!-- end item 479e598c-957a-4885-a1ff-a183e8a96e4e -->","topic":{"id":"17c8e063-0f1d-5d60-8e45-86077215a930","topicId":"f866f70e-e1a9-45c7-a881-fdc6b7629bfb","topicName":"Acute childhood limp","slug":"acute-childhood-limp","lastRevised":"Last revised in September 2020","chapters":[{"id":"2add8668-a668-5c93-97d8-179c17db22e4","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"fca68b5f-ef77-5cae-9e6b-85e1f467521e","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"29985e61-3fe0-5ae8-854b-587f4765a713","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"3719e340-713f-50c1-9aaa-5ec90a98e0a1","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"b6524393-cae9-5e1b-94a4-5d80be24b728","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"ee0ee429-c969-539b-84ca-9d3a44e4083c","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","subChapters":[{"id":"b7da222b-8439-5bec-ab0f-e2cb32574650","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"150ed265-6f75-57e8-bbaf-b6d45042f38f","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"c4820ad5-6470-57d4-8f74-7f2d079cfe19","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"304b905a-4cf3-54a0-a8f8-99fe474aa953","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"616f2518-9f78-52f5-9b83-620d7839c170","slug":"qipp-options-for-local-implementation","fullItemName":"QIPP - Options for local implementation"},{"id":"08199b7e-8776-50ef-9cc0-4cef3aba81c5","slug":"nice-quality-standards","fullItemName":"NICE quality standards"}]},{"id":"3327afee-e848-5b91-9b6f-c9bec83c1d37","full